     <div id="post-6864" class="post-6864 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail category-linux-tips linux-tips" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting" itemprop="blogPost"> 
      <div class="entry-header"> 
       <h1 class="entry-title" itemprop="headline">Convert Images Between Formats via the Command Line in Ubuntu</h1> 
      </div> 
      <div class="entry-content" itemprop="articleBody"> 
       <span class="post-ad-top adsense-block" id="adsense-block-5"> 
        <div class="adsense-block-wrap" style="width: 336px;"> 
         <ins class="adsbygoogle adsense-block-5" style="display:block" data-ad-client="ca-pub-8156617711959851" data-ad-slot="8605969107" data-ad-format="rectangle"> </ins> 
        </div> <script>
		(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
		</script> </span> 
       <div class="KonaBody">
        <p>If you need to convert an image from one format to another you can use <strong>GIMP</strong> to do so, but there is an easier way. You can use <strong>ImageMagick</strong>, which provides a way to convert images using the command line.</p> 
        <h4>Installing ImageMagick</h4> 
        <p><strong>ImageMagick</strong> may already be installed. You can check in the <strong>Synaptic Package Manager</strong>. Select <strong>Administration | Synaptic Package Manager</strong> from the <strong>System</strong> menu.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/01_selecting_synaptic_package_manager.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/01_selecting_synaptic_package_manager_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Accessing the Synaptic Package Manager" width="505" height="439"></a></p> 
        <p>In the <strong>Quick search</strong> edit box on the <strong>Synaptic Package Manager</strong> window, enter <strong>imagemagick</strong>. The results of the search start to display as you type your search term. If <strong>ImageMagick</strong> is already installed, the check box next to the program name will be filled in green, and you can skip to the <strong>Converting an Image Using ImageMagick</strong> section below.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/02_searching_for_imagemagick_in_synaptic.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/02_searching_for_imagemagick_in_synaptic_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Searching for ImageMagick" width="580" height="457"></a></p> 
        <p>If <strong>ImageMagick</strong> is not already installed, click on the check box to open a pop-up menu. Select the <strong>Mark for Installation</strong> option from the menu.</p>
        <div class="code-block code-block-1" style="margin: 8px auto; text-align: center; clear: both;"> 
         <!-- /22152718/HelpDeskGeek_in-content --> 
         <div id="div-gpt-ad-1465312641547-0"> 
          <script type="text/javascript">
googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1465312641547-0'); });
</script> 
         </div>
        </div> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/03_mark_for_installation.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/03_mark_for_installation_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Marking ImageMagick for installation" width="407" height="364"></a></p> 
        <p>A yellow arrow displays over the check box next to <strong>imagemagick</strong>, indicating it is marked for installation. Click the <strong>Apply</strong> button to continue with the installation.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/04_apply_all_marked_changes.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/04_apply_all_marked_changes_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Apply all marked changes" width="386" height="212"></a></p> 
        <p>A <strong>Summary</strong> screen displays listing all the changes that will be made. Click the <strong>Apply</strong> button.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/05_summary_of_changes_to_be_applied.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/05_summary_of_changes_to_be_applied_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Summary of the changes to be applied" width="559" height="457"></a></p> 
        <p>The installation progress displays.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/06_applying_changes.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/06_applying_changes_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Applying changes" width="528" height="301"></a></p> 
        <p>The <strong>Changes applied</strong> dialog box displays when the installation is finished. Click the <strong>Close</strong> button.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/07_changes_applied.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/07_changes_applied_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Changes applied" width="529" height="241"></a></p> 
        <p>Select <strong>Quit</strong> from the <strong>File</strong> menu to close the <strong>Synaptic Package Manager</strong>.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/08_closing_synaptic_package_manager.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/08_closing_synaptic_package_manager_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Closing the Synaptic Package Manager" width="427" height="301"></a></p> 
        <h4>Converting an Image Using ImageMagick</h4> 
        <p>Once <strong>ImageMagick</strong> is installed, simply use the convert command in a terminal window. For example, the following command will convert a <strong>PNG</strong> file to a <strong>JPEG</strong> file.</p> 
        <blockquote>
         <p>$ convert sample.png sample.jpg</p>
        </blockquote> 
        <p>However, converting an image into a <strong>JPEG</strong> sacrifices image quality for file size. There is a command switch, <strong>–quality</strong>, that allows you to specify the quality of the resulting <strong>.jpg</strong> file. You can set a value between <strong>0</strong> (poorest quality) to <strong>100</strong> (highest quality). Remember that the better the quality (the higher the number), the bigger the file size. Generally, a value between <strong>60</strong> and <strong>80</strong> is good enough for most uses.</p> 
        <p>The following command converts sample.png into a <strong>JPEG</strong> image with a quality of <strong>80</strong>.</p> 
        <blockquote>
         <p>$ convert –quality 80 sample.png sample.jpg</p>
        </blockquote> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/09_converting_png_to_jpg.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/09_converting_png_to_jpg_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Converting a .png file to a .jpg file" width="580" height="394"></a></p> 
        <p>A <strong>JPEG</strong> file called <strong>sample.jpg</strong> is created in the same directory as the original <strong>.png</strong> file. There is a quick way to view the converted image. The default image viewer in Ubuntu is called <strong>Eye of Gnome</strong>. Using <strong>Eye of Gnome</strong>, you can quickly view the following images: ani, bmp, gif, ico, jpeg, pcx, png, pnm, ras, svg, tga, tiff, wbmp, xbm, and xpm.</p> 
        <p>To run <strong>Eye of Gnome</strong> from the command line, simply type <strong>eog</strong>. So, to view the converted image file type the following command:</p> 
        <blockquote>
         <p>$ eog sample.jpg</p>
        </blockquote> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/10_command_to_view_an_image.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/10_command_to_view_an_image_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Command for viewing an image" width="580" height="394"></a></p> 
        <p>The viewer opens displaying the specified image.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/11_viewing_an_image_in_eog.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/11_viewing_an_image_in_eog_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Viewing an image in Eye of Gnome" width="580" height="527"></a></p> 
        <p>To close <strong>Eye of Gnome</strong>, select <strong>Close</strong> from the <strong>File</strong> menu.</p> 
        <p><a href="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/12_closing_eog.png"><img style="display: block; float: none; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border-width: 0px;" itemprop="image" data-original="https://10629-presscdn-0-58-pagely.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/pictures/2010/05/12_closing_eog_thumb.png" border="0" alt="Closing Eye of Gnome" width="382" height="360"></a></p> 
        <p>If you prefer using the command line to perform tasks, click <a href="http://www.imagemagick.org/Usage/" target="_blank">here</a> to access a web page that provides a set of examples using <strong>ImageMagick</strong> from the command line.</p> 
        <p>by Lori Kaufman</p>
